1 that are unsatisfactory or inappropriate, and to be provided with information about a formal process
2 for making complaints without fear of retaliation, harassment or punishment.
3 (2) To be notified of, and provided with transportation to, court hearings and reviews by local
4 citizen review boards pertaining to the foster child’s case. [when the matters to be considered or de-
5 cided upon at the hearings and reviews are appropriate for the foster child, taking into account the age
6 and developmental stage of the foster child.]
7 (3) To be provided with written contact information of specific individuals whom the foster child
8 may contact regarding complaints, concerns or violations of rights, that is updated as necessary and
9 kept current.
10 (4) To be protected from abuse, exploitation, neglect, intimidation, retaliation and
11 wrongful use of restraint or seclusion.
12 (5) To regularly attend school and to have access to a free and appropriate public edu-
13 cation.
14 (6) To be assigned an attorney to represent the foster child’s interests and to have un-
15 impeded and unmonitored contact with that attorney.
16 (7) To have unimpeded and unmonitored contact, as applicable, with the Residential Fa-
17 cilities Ombudsman, the Children’s Advocate or a foster care ombudsman who has been
18 formally designated by the Children’s Advocate or the Department of Human Services.
19 (8) To have an attorney or court-appointed advocate of the foster child’s choosing present
20 for any interview with law enforcement or abuse investigators, regardless of whether the
21 foster child is interviewed as a witness, a victim or a subject individual.
22 (9) To maintain and have access to personal belongings including but not limited to
23 clothing, books, toys, photographs and musical instruments.
24 (10) To be present at court hearings, including to be present at all court hearings re-
25 garding the child’s case.
26 (11) To transport belongings and personal effects in an appropriate luggage carrier when
27 entering into or transitioning or exiting from foster care.
28 [(4)] (12) When a foster child is 14 years of age or older, to be provided with written information
29 within 60 days of the date of any placement or any change in placement, regarding:
30 (a) How to establish a bank account in the foster child’s name as allowed under state law;
31 (b) How to acquire a driver license as allowed under state law;
32 (c) How to remain in foster care after reaching 18 years of age;
33 (d) The availability of a tuition and fee waiver for a current or former foster child under ORS
34 350.300;
35 (e) How to obtain a copy of the foster child’s credit report, if any;
36 (f) How to obtain medical, dental, vision, mental health services or other treatment, including
37 services and treatments available without parental consent under state law; and
38 (g) A transition toolkit, including a comprehensive transition plan.
39 [(5)] (13) With respect to a foster child’s rights under the federal and state constitutions, laws,
40 including case law, rules and regulations:
41 (a) To receive a document setting forth such rights that is age-appropriate and developmentally
42 appropriate within [60] seven days of the date of any placement or any change in placement;
43 (b) To have a document setting forth such rights that is age-appropriate and developmentally
44 appropriate posted at the residences of all foster parents, child-caring agencies and independent
45 resident facilities;
