13
14 CHILDREN IN CARE
15
16 SECTION 6. (1) The provisions of ORS 418.257 to 418.259 do not apply to investigations
17 of reports of suspected abuse, as defined in ORS 418.257, of a child in care if the suspected
18 abuse is committed by the child in care’s parent.
19 (2) The provisions of ORS 418.521 and 418.523 do not apply to the restraint or involuntary
20 seclusion of a child in care if the child in care is placed in the restraint or involuntary se-
21 clusion by the parent of the child in care.
22 (3) As used in this section, “child in care,” “involuntary seclusion” and “restraint” have
23 the meanings given those terms in ORS 418.519.
24 SECTION 7. ORS 409.185 is amended to read:
25 409.185. (1) The Director of Human Services shall oversee the development of standards and
26 procedures for assessment, investigation and enforcement of child protective services.
27 (2)(a) The Department of Human Services shall take action to implement the provision of child
28 protective services as outlined in ORS 417.705 to 417.800 and based on the recommendations in the
29 1992 “Oregon Child Protective Services Performance Study” published by the University of Southern
30 Maine.
31 (b) In all substantiated cases of child abuse and neglect, the role of the department is to com-
32 plete a comprehensive family assessment of risk of abuse or neglect, or both, assess service needs
33 and provide immediate protective services as necessary.
34 (c) The department shall provide remedial services needed to ensure the safety of the child.
35 (d) In all cases of child abuse and neglect for which a criminal investigation is conducted, the
36 role of law enforcement agencies is to provide a legally sound, child sensitive investigation of
37 whether abuse or neglect or both have occurred and to gather other evidence and perform other
38 responsibilities in accordance with interagency agreements.
39 (e) The department and law enforcement agencies shall conduct the investigation and assess-
40 ment concurrently, based upon the protocols and procedures of the county child abuse multidisci-
41 plinary team in each jurisdiction.
42 (f) When the department and law enforcement agencies conduct a joint investigation and as-
43 sessment, the activities of the department and agencies are to be clearly differentiated by the pro-
44 tocols of the county child abuse multidisciplinary team.
45 (g) Nothing in this subsection is intended to be inconsistent with ORS 418.702, 418.747 and
[6]

SB 1533
1 418.748 and ORS chapter 419B.
2 (h) In all cases of child abuse for which an investigation is conducted, the department shall
3 provide a child’s parent, guardian or caregiver with a clear written explanation of the investigation
4 process, the court hearing process and the rights of the parent, guardian or caregiver in the abuse
5 investigation and in the court proceedings related to the abuse investigation. When the depart-
6 ment provides the written explanation under this paragraph to a child’s parent or guardian,
7 the department shall include a disclosure that the representative of the department is acting
8 on behalf of the department and cannot provide legal advice to the parent or guardian.
9 (3) Upon receipt of a recommendation of the Children’s Advocate under ORS 417.815 (2)(e), the
10 department shall implement the recommendation or give the Children’s Advocate written notice of
11 an intent not to implement the recommendation.
